article.headline: Marbury misses late 3-point shot
article.linkText: Celtic pride: Boston extends win streak to 6
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Written off in the Eastern Conference playoff race less than two weeks ago, the Boston Celtics have found a way to stay in the hunt. Paul Pierce scored 23 points, including an off-balance jumper as the shot clock expired with 24 seconds left, to lead the Celtics an 87-84 victory over the New York Knicks on Tuesday night. The win was the sixth in a row for Boston, which had lost 13 of 14 and was a season-worst 13 games below .500 (23-36) before the current winning streak. The victory tied them with the Knicks for sixth place in the East. "It just seems like a light switch clicked on," Pierce said. "We understand what it is going to take defensively and we are doing it. That is what is really taking care of things. We know we have the offensive weapons to play with anybody in the league." One of the Celtics' new faces is Ricky Davis, who was traded from Cleveland on December 15 -- after the Celtics had won five in a row under former coach Jim O'Brien. "Guys just woke up and realized that we are still in the playoff race and that we are capable of beating anyone," said Davis, who had 15 points. After trailing most of the game, the Knicks took their first lead since the first quarter when Allan Houston's jumper made it 74-72 with 6:53 left. Tim Thomas' 3-pointer with 3:26 left expanded the Knicks lead to 81-78 lead, but a free throw by Pierce and two by Mark Blount tied it. The Celtics then took the lead for good when Blount's dunk with 1:06 left made it 83-81. Thomas made one of two free throws before Pierce made his corner jumper while being tightly guarded by Shandon Anderson. "That's an incredible shot," Penny Hardaway said. "That's just Paul Pierce being Paul Pierce. He made a great shot." Thomas' drive brought the Knicks within one, then Pierce gave Boston a two-point lead when he made one of two free throws with 17 seconds left. On their final possession, the Knicks ran the clock down before Stephon Marbury launched a long straightaway 3-pointer that hit the front of the rim. "I was open. I had a good look. I'd take that shot again," Marbury said. "If I make it, we win, and I thought it was going in." Davis grabbed the rebound with 0.5 seconds left and was fouled. He made the first and purposely missed the second. The Celtics led by as many as eight in the first half, and Brandon Hunter's layup to begin the second half gave the Celtics their biggest lead of the game. The Knicks kept chipping away, and Houston's 3-pointer brought them within 57-56 with 4:19 left in the third quarter. Walter McCarty's 3-pointer re-established a four-point lead, and Boston managed to hold a 62-60 lead going into the fourth. Blount finished with 15 points and 17 rebounds for Boston. Pierce added eight assists, eight rebounds and three steals. Chucky Atkins, who added 14 points and went 4-of-7 on 3-pointers, joined the Celtics on February 19. Boston is 6-1 since then. "Chucky is a real consummate pro. He is excited about playing heavy minutes and he has great leadership skills," Celtics interim head coach John Carroll said. Houston scored 23 and Thomas had 17 for the Knicks, who had their three-game winning streak snapped.

Game notes
The Knicks won the season series 3-1, but haven't swept the Celtics since 1996-97. ... The win was the Celtics' 250th all-time vs. the Knicks. They lead the series 250-165. ... Kurt Thomas signed a four-year contract extension with the Knicks before the game.
